SP  - 1523
EP  - 1569
VL  - 84
IS  - 4
KW  - Search and matching
KW  - unemployment
KW  - business cycles
KW  - wage inertia
KW  - Nash bargaining
KW  - alternating offer bargaining
KW  - wage rules
KW  - unemployment benefits
KW  - Bayesian estimation
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA11776
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We develop and estimate a general equilibrium search and matching model that accounts for key business cycle properties of macroeconomic aggregates, including labor market variables. In sharp contrast to leading New Keynesian models, we do not impose wage inertia. Instead we derive wage inertia from our specification of how firms and workers negotiate wages. Our model outperforms a variant of the standard New Keynesian Calvo sticky wage model. According to our estimated model, there is a critical interaction between the degree of price stickiness, monetary policy, and the duration of an increase in unemployment benefits.
ER  - 

